[Student "S"]
{Partner's 2NT is lebensohl, requesting that you bid 3\C. You obey and partner now bids 3\H.  

Partner's 2NT is lebensohl, requesting that you bid 3\C. You obey and partner now bids 3\H. 

The cue-bid is Stayman, asking if you have 4 \Ss. However, since it was a DELAYED cue-bid it also shows stopper(s) in the opponent's overcalled suit. Since you do not have 4 \Ss you go ahead and bid 3NT.

North plays 3NT.

East naturally attacks in his suit, leading the \HQ.

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 2 : \D = 2 : \C = 2 :: Total = 7

There are several possibilities for extra winners. The \DQ might drop - or the finesse might work, providing one winner. The \Cs might split 3-2, giving you one extra winner. The \S honors might be split (or East might hold both) so the double finesse would give you two winners. Since your minor suit hopes require that BOTH of them work, your best bet is the double \S finesse. 

You do not need to hold up on the \H because you will be finessing twice into West, and he cannot possibly have more than two \Hs, probably only one. Come to your hand with a \C, play the \SJ and let it ride. West wins the \SQ and plays another \C. Win this one and finesse the \S again. When this finesse works you can return to your hand with a \D and repeat the finesse.

The double finesse has a 75% chance of success since it only requires that East hold either the \SK, \SQ, or both.

Even if West held both honors you would <b>STILL</b> have established one \S winner and would have the possibility of a \D finesse. }
[Play "W"]HQ

